DOMINICAN TREE HOUSE STAY GIVEAWAY!! 🌴🇩🇴

We are giving you and a friend a chance to win an epic trip to the Dominican Republic!

The winner will receive 5 days/4 nights and 2x $500 airplane ticket credit to stay at the beautiful eco-resort @dominicantreehousevillage. All meals, bottomless local rum drinks, juices, sodas, water included! This trip also includes 2 zipline excursions, bicycle rentals, and nightly onsite activities.

Explore the lush jungle of the Samana province in the Dominican Republic, a natural resort of open-air cabins perched above the forest floor!

To Enter:
1) Follow @dominicantreehousevillage, @wonderlustcollective, @fastnewsfacts
2) Tag friends in separate comments
3) Visit the link in our bio and enter your email
1 Comment = 1 Entry. Unlimited Entries
**BONUS** Share this Post in your Story and Tag Us

A winner will be chosen on 9/3 and announced via @wonderlustcollective.

Winner has until the end of August 2022 to reserve. Not redeemable for cash value.
*
Subject to availability blackout dates.
*
Travel to and from location is not provided
-
We will never DM you any links to claim prize!
-
Good luck!! ❤️
-
(This giveaway is not sponsored by Instagram)

node.text:
Spotting the rare pink dolphin 🐬💖

While we’re not sure whether this video was edited or not, pink dolphins actually exist. The endangered Amazon river dolphin and Indo-Pacific humpback dolphin both have a pink shade to them (especially males). Have you heard of them before?

via @discoverwildlife

To Enter:
1. Follow @nuii_icecream_global 
2. Upload an image to Instagram, tagging @nuii_icecream_global and #MyNuiiAdventure

Winners selection to be judged on originality, quality, unexpected locations and creativity

We can’t wait to see what you guys share.

Competiton ends on 6th September 2021
 
Good luck! 🐘

node.text:
Have you ever seen this colorful community? 😍 Its located in Rainbow island, Iran. This colorful residence of dirt domes was built by Nader Khalili and its a beach front residence community.

Hormuz Island sits south of Iran in the Persian Gulf and is often called “rainbow island” in reference to the multicolored sand that makes it a popular tourist spot. In an effort to reflect the colorful landscape and topography, ZAV Architects has designed a small settlement comprising multicolor domes that overlap in interesting combinations to create homes and cultural programs such as laundry services, praying areas, and a café.

This multipurpose settlement, referred to as Presence in Hormuz, serves as more than just a bright and welcoming accommodation, though—it is the embodiment of a paradigm shift for the community. “The local inhabitants of the beautiful, touristic and politically strategic island,” the architects explain, “struggle economically, getting involved in illegal trafficking activities using their boats.” This urban development project aims to reinvigorate the local economy by utilizing members of the community—craftsmen and unskilled workers alike.
